---
import CalculatorLayout from '@layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import { PrintOnDemandCalc } from '@components/calculators/PrintOnDemandCalc';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How much profit can you make with print-on-demand?',
    answer:
      'Typical POD profit margins range from 20-40% depending on product type, platform, and whether you sell through a marketplace. A $29 t-shirt on Printful might net $10-12 profit selling direct, or $7-9 after Etsy fees. Volume is key — 50+ monthly sales is where POD becomes meaningful income.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which print-on-demand platform is cheapest?',
    answer:
      'Printify generally has the lowest base costs because they aggregate multiple print providers. Printful costs more but offers better quality, branding options (custom labels, inserts), and more reliable fulfillment. Merch by Amazon has zero upfront costs but takes a large cut (67.5%).',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I sell POD on Etsy or my own store?',
    answer:
      'Etsy gives you marketplace traffic but charges 6.5% transaction + 3% processing + listing fees. Your own Shopify/WooCommerce store has no marketplace fees but requires driving your own traffic. Many sellers start on Etsy for visibility, then transition to their own store as they build an audience.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What are the best-selling print-on-demand products?',
    answer:
      'T-shirts are the highest volume POD product, followed by hoodies, mugs, and phone cases. Stickers have the lowest production cost and highest margin percentage. Posters work well for niche art. Choose products that match your audience — a fitness brand sells more hoodies than mugs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Merch by Amazon compare to Printful?',
    answer:
      'Merch by Amazon gives you access to Amazon marketplace traffic with zero upfront costs, but you earn only 32.5% royalty and have limited customization. Printful gives you full control over pricing, branding, and marketplace choice, but you handle marketing. MBA is best for passive income; Printful is best for building a brand.',
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  {
    name: 'Etsy Fee Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate true profit per item after Etsy fees',
    href: '/creator/etsy-fee-calculator',
    category: 'Creator',
  },
  {
    name: 'Gumroad Revenue Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate digital product revenue after fees',
    href: '/creator/gumroad-calculator',
    category: 'Creator',
  },
  {
    name: 'Dropshipping Margin Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate dropshipping profits and break-even',
    href: '/side-hustle/dropshipping-margin-calculator',
    category: 'Side Hustle',
  },
  {
    name: 'Reselling Profit Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate buy-sell margins and ROI',
    href: '/side-hustle/reselling-profit-calculator',
    category: 'Side Hustle',
  },
];
---

<CalculatorLayout
  ogImage="/og-images/print-on-demand-profit.png"
  title="Print-on-Demand Profit Calculator - POD Margins & Revenue"
  description="Calculate your print-on-demand profit per unit and monthly revenue. Compare Printful, Printify, and Merch by Amazon costs. Free POD calculator."
  calculatorName="Print-on-Demand Profit Calculator"
  category="Creator"
  categorySlug="creator"
  slug="print-on-demand-profit-calculator"
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
>
  <Fragment slot="intro">
    <section class="mb-8">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>Print-on-Demand Economics: What Determines Your Profit</h2>
        <p>Print-on-demand (POD) eliminates inventory risk by producing products only after a customer orders. You design, a fulfillment partner prints and ships, and you keep the difference between your selling price and their production cost. The model is simple, but the margin math is more nuanced than most sellers realize. Platform fees, marketplace commissions, shipping costs, returns, and advertising can erode a seemingly healthy margin to single digits if you are not careful.</p>
        <p>The three major POD fulfillment providers -- Printful, Printify, and Merch by Amazon -- each take fundamentally different approaches to pricing. Printful charges higher base costs but offers premium quality and branding options. Printify aggregates multiple print providers to offer the lowest base costs. Merch by Amazon handles everything but pays only a fixed royalty percentage. Your choice of provider, combined with where you sell (own store vs. Etsy vs. Amazon), creates a cost stack that this calculator models precisely.</p>
        <h3>The POD Profit Formula</h3>
        <p>Your profit per unit is: <strong>Selling Price - Base Cost - Marketplace Fees - Shipping - (Ad Spend / Units Sold)</strong>. A $29.99 t-shirt on Printful with a $12.50 base cost, sold through Etsy (6.5% + 3% processing), yields roughly $11.50 per unit before advertising. If you spend $100/month on ads and sell 30 shirts, that is another $3.33 per unit, bringing net profit to around $8.17 per shirt. This calculator runs these layered calculations automatically so you can compare scenarios quickly.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <PrintOnDemandCalc client:visible />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>How to Use the Print-on-Demand Profit Calculator</h2>
        <p>Select your POD platform and product type, set your selling price, and enter expected monthly sales to see your per-unit profit and monthly revenue. The calculator automatically pulls in base production costs for each platform and product combination.</p>
        <h3>Quick Mode</h3>
        <p>Enter your platform, product type, selling price, and monthly sales volume. The calculator shows your profit per unit, monthly net profit, and profit margin. Use this to quickly compare profitability across different platforms and products.</p>
        <h3>Advanced Mode</h3>
        <p>Advanced mode adds marketplace fees (Etsy, Amazon), shipping charges, advertising costs, design expenses, and return rates. If you sell through Etsy, the calculator stacks Etsy's fees on top of POD production costs so you can see the full cost picture. Model different scenarios by adjusting your marketplace and ad budget to find the most profitable setup.</p>
        <h3>Choosing the Right Platform</h3>
        <p>Printify offers the lowest base costs by connecting you to multiple print providers. Printful costs more but provides superior quality control, custom branding, and faster shipping. Merch by Amazon eliminates upfront costs entirely but limits your margin to a 32.5% royalty. Consider your priorities: lowest cost (Printify), best brand experience (Printful), or zero risk (MBA).</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="deep-dive">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>Base Production Costs by Platform and Product</h2>
        <p>Production costs vary significantly across POD providers and product types. The table below shows approximate base costs (before shipping and marketplace fees) for the most popular product categories. These are the costs you pay to the fulfillment provider per unit.</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Product</th>
              <th>Printful</th>
              <th>Printify</th>
              <th>Merch by Amazon*</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Standard T-Shirt</td>
              <td>$12.50</td>
              <td>$7.50 - $10.00</td>
              <td>N/A (royalty model)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Premium T-Shirt</td>
              <td>$15.00</td>
              <td>$10.00 - $13.00</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Hoodie</td>
              <td>$28.00</td>
              <td>$18.00 - $24.00</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Mug (11oz)</td>
              <td>$7.50</td>
              <td>$5.00 - $7.00</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Phone Case</td>
              <td>$10.00</td>
              <td>$6.00 - $8.50</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Poster (18x24)</td>
              <td>$9.00</td>
              <td>$5.00 - $7.00</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Sticker Sheet</td>
              <td>$2.50</td>
              <td>$1.50 - $2.50</td>
              <td>N/A</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>*Merch by Amazon uses a royalty model: you earn approximately 32.5% of the list price on standard products. On a $19.99 t-shirt, that is roughly $6.50 per sale with zero upfront cost.</p>

        <h2>Worked Example: Comparing Sales Channels</h2>
        <p>An artist sells a $28.00 t-shirt design. Here is how profit per unit changes depending on fulfillment provider and sales channel:</p>
        <p><strong>Printful + Own Shopify Store:</strong> Base cost $12.50, Shopify processing ~$0.81 (2.9%), no marketplace fee. Profit per unit: $14.69. Margin: 52.5%.</p>
        <p><strong>Printful + Etsy:</strong> Base cost $12.50, Etsy transaction fee $1.82 (6.5%), Etsy processing $0.84 (3%), listing fee $0.20. Profit per unit: $12.64. Margin: 45.1%.</p>
        <p><strong>Printify + Etsy:</strong> Base cost $8.50 (lowest provider), Etsy fees $2.86 total. Profit per unit: $16.64. Margin: 59.4%.</p>
        <p><strong>Merch by Amazon:</strong> Royalty on $28.00 ~ $9.10 (32.5%). No other costs. Profit: $9.10. Margin: 32.5%. Zero effort on fulfillment or customer service.</p>
        <p>The Printify + Etsy combination delivers the highest margin, but requires managing both a fulfillment integration and an Etsy storefront. Merch by Amazon offers the lowest margin but also the lowest effort and zero financial risk.</p>

        <h2>Pricing Strategy for POD Products</h2>
        <p><strong>Research competitor pricing first.</strong> Search Etsy and Amazon for similar designs in your niche. If competing t-shirts sell for $22-26, pricing at $32 will tank your conversion rate regardless of design quality. Price within the competitive range, then differentiate on design and brand.</p>
        <p><strong>Account for all costs before setting price.</strong> Many new POD sellers set a price that looks profitable based on base cost alone, then discover that marketplace fees, shipping, and advertising eat their margin. Use this calculator to model the full cost stack before committing to a price point.</p>
        <p><strong>Use tiered pricing across products.</strong> Stickers and small prints at $5-10 serve as entry points that build customer trust. T-shirts at $25-30 are the volume driver. Hoodies at $45-55 and premium products drive higher average order values. Offer bundles to increase cart size.</p>
        <p><strong>Factor in return rates.</strong> POD return rates average 3-8% depending on product category. Apparel has higher returns due to sizing issues. Each return costs you the original production and shipping with no revenue. Build a 5% return buffer into your pricing model to protect your margins.</p>

        <h2>Scaling Beyond Hobby Income</h2>
        <p>The break-even point for most POD businesses is 20-30 sales per month, where revenue covers any fixed costs like Shopify subscriptions or design tool licenses. To reach meaningful income (over $1,000/month profit), most sellers need 80-150 monthly sales depending on product mix and margins. The path to scale involves expanding your design catalog (more designs means more search surface area), testing multiple product types per design, and reinvesting 15-25% of revenue into advertising. Sellers who treat POD as a portfolio business with 50+ active designs consistently outperform those who rely on a handful of products.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
